Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

See this Data Dictionary to understand the dataset's variables.

In [10]:
# Convert ProsperRating & IncomeRange to categorical 
cat_columns = {'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['N/A','HR','E','D','C', 'B', 'A', 'AA'],
                    'IncomeRange':['$0','$1-24,999','$25,000-49,999','$50,000-74,999','$75,000-99,999','$100,000+']}

for col in cat_columns:
    cat_col = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = cat_columns[col])
    df_loan[col] = df_loan[col].astype(cat_col)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113937 rows and 25 columns. Majority of the columns are numeric but we also have categorical variables and datetime variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main interest of exploring this dataset would be the Loan Original Amount. I will also work on Borrower Rate, Borrower APR, Prosper Score, CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper, Borrower Occupation, Borrower State etc.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe borrower's Loan Status and Employment Status will have a strong impact on loan and the features we are trying to explore. Also the Income Range can be a pointer here and the Term (lenght of the loan) may have an effect.

Univariate Exploration¶

For this phase, we would be exploring the different variables in the dataset to see how they're distributed, their absolute frequencies and to generally understand their relevance in the entire exploration.

In [14]:
# creating a function for chart name, x and y labels, to avoid repetition in using the plt function
def labels(a,b,c):
    """
    This function gives chart title, x and y axis
    --------
    It aims to avoid repetition by taking in three parameters for the chart title and both the x and y axis labels
    """
    return plt.title(a),plt.ylabel(b),plt.xlabel(c)

Question 1¶

What is the Borrower APR (Annual Percentage Rate) distribution?

Visualization¶

In [15]:
# Distribution of Borrower APR in percentage 
BorrowerAPR_pct = df_loan['BorrowerAPR']*100
bins = np.arange(df_loan['BorrowerAPR'].min()*100, df_loan['BorrowerAPR'].max()*100+2, 2)

plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
plt.hist(x = BorrowerAPR_pct, bins = bins)
plt.xticks([5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40], ['5','10', '15', '20', '25', '30', '35', '40'])
labels('Borrower APR Distribution (%)','Count','Borrower Annual Percentage Rate (%)');

Observation¶

We can infer that the Borrower APR is normally distrubuted with a peak between 15% and 20% in addition we have some increase in the 35%.

Question 4¶

What is the Proper Score disribution?

  • ProsperScore: A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score.

Visualization¶

In [21]:
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.countplot(data=df_loan, x= 'ProsperScore', color=base_color)
labels('Prosper Score Distribution','count','Prosper Score');

Observation¶

We can see a modal score of 4 and we can tell that most borrowers fall within 4-8 risk score. Also we can infer that borrowers with the highest risk score of 1 are the least population in the dataset. Another observation is a category of borrowers having a risk score of 11 whereas the prosper score ranges from 0-10. This could be as a result of incorrect data.

Question 5¶

In which caterogy is the reason why loans was taken?

  • ListingCategory: The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans

Visualization¶

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
order = loan['ListingCategory (numeric)'].value_counts().index
sb.countplot(data=loan, x='ListingCategory (numeric)', color=base_color, order=order)
plt.xlabel('ListingCategory (numeric)')
plt.title('Listing Category',fontsize=15);

Observation¶

We see that Debt Consolidation is the major reason why people take out new loans. Home improvement loans and Business loans trail behind some loans termed 'Other' or 'Not available' to signify that the borrower didn't specify their reason. Green loans and loans for boats and RVs were the least types of listings created. People also took out loans to get engagement rings.

Conclusions¶

Overall, we found that though business was amongst the top 3 reasons people take loan, self-employed people took less loans than people who are employed. We found that the higher the salary income does not affect taking a loan as people who earn 100k+ still make up a huge part of the population that collect loans while people who earned more were generally granted high loan amounts. Also, we saw people in California tend to take more loans and Professionals and Computer Programmers took more loans than people from other occupations. 3 years was also the most popular loan term as opposed to 5 years and 1 year.

Based on the data we saw that people with good credit score are the ones that take loans the most, we can call them responsible debtors as they pay back their loan on time. Further research can be done to generate this insight. An interesting insight we saw was that Judges are one of the least set of category that take loans. Are they very well paid? What is the reason. Further research can also be done to generate this insight.
